```

What's going on here?

Consider the following code:

```PowerShell
function AssertSomething {
    param (
        [parameter(ValueFromPipeline)]
        $InputObject
    )
    process
    {
        # Is there a robust way to distinguish between these
        # two cases:
        #  1.  $InputObject is the only element emitted by
        #      the enumerator of the object piped to the function
        #      at the call site.
        #      
        #  2.  $InputObject is the object piped to the function
        #      at the call site.
    }
}

# For example, 
@(1) | AssertSomething # I would like this call to throw
1 | AssertSomething # and this call to succeed.
```

Is there a way to robustly distinguish between the two call sites on the basis of whether the object piped to `AssertSomething` was enumerated?

### Background

I've been experimenting with improved assertion commands for use with Pester to validate return values.  Wherever a return value encounters `|` on its way to the command there is a potential for PowerShell to enumerate and pass the object contents rather than pass the object itself.  Here is an example:

```PowerShell
function AssertProperty {
    param (
        [Parameter(Position = 1)] $PropertyName,
        [Parameter(Position = 2)] $eq,
        [Parameter(ValueFromPipeline)] $InputObject
    )
    process
    {
        if ( $InputObject.$PropertyName -eq $eq ) 
        {
            return
        }
        throw "Property $PropertyName was $($InputObject.$PropertyName)."
    }
}

function SomeUserFunction {
    ,@([pscustomobject]@{Count=2})
}

Describe SomeUserFunction {
    It 'returns an object whose Count property is 2' {
        $r = SomeUserFunction
        $r | AssertProperty Count 2
    }
}
```

This test passes even though `$r.Count` is 1.  The cause of the false negative is obvious in this contrived example.  In real tests, however, I've found this situation to be much less obvious and much more pernicious.

I've experimented with a few different promising strategies for compensating for this situation, but so far all of them involve somewhat unnatural PowerShell. ( eg. `AssertProperty $r Count 2` or `subject $r | AssertProperty Count 2`).  The ability to detect when the object piped to `AssertProperty` was enumerated would open up some other strategies.

Add the following VS Code settings to have a more consistent `PowerShell` style already at the PR stage. It is mainly based on the [K&R/OTBS](https://github.com/PoshCode/PowerShellPracticeAndStyle/issues/81#issuecomment-285835313) style, which basically means braces are on the same line and that else, catch, and other keywords are "cuddled" (e.g. `} else {`)
Personally I'd prefer rather the [Stroustrup](https://github.com/PoshCode/PowerShellPracticeAndStyle/issues/81#issuecomment-285835361) style where there is no "cuddling" but I have seen that the `K&R/OTBS` is used more often in the codebase.

````
